{{Infobox person | name = Candace Chong Mui Ngam | image = CandaceChong.jpg | alt = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software --> | caption = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = {{Birth date and age |1976|09|09}} | birth_place = [[Hong Kong]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | nationality = | other_names = | occupation = Playwright | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }} '''Candace Chong Mui Ngam''' ({{zh|c=莊梅岩 |j=zong1 mui4 ngaam4}}) is a Chinese playwright from [[Hong Kong]] who has written scripts for play such as The ''French Kiss (2005)'', ''Murder in San José (2009)'' and ''The Wild Boar (2012)''. She has won the Hong Kong Drama Award four times in the category of Best Script and in 2010 was given the title best drama artist by the [[Hong Kong Arts Development Council]].<ref name=":0" />
==Life and career== Chong was born in Hong Kong in 1976 and attended [[St. Paul's Co-educational College]] before deciding to study psychology at the [[Chinese University of Hong Kong]]. After graduating in 1999 she majored in play-writing at the [[Hong Kong Academy for Performing Arts]] and then traveled to London to complete her master's degree at [[Royal Holloway, University of London]].<ref name=":0">{{cite news|last1=Leung|first1=Jancie|title=Candace Chong: The playwright who draws inspiration from a complicated world|url=http://www.scmp.com/magazines/style/article/1049584/candace-chong-playwright-who-draws-inspiration-complicated-world|accessdate=16 November 2017|publisher=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=9 October 2012}}</ref>
After completing her formal education, Chong joined the [[Chung Ying Theatre Company]] where she wrote her award-winning plays<ref>{{cite news|title=Making words sing|url=http://www.scmp.com/article/969050/making-words-sing|accessdate=16 November 2017|publisher=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=29 May 2011}}</ref> ''Alive in the Mortuary (2003)'', ''Shall We Go to Mars? (2005)'', ''French Kiss (2005)'', ''Murder in San José (2009)'' and ''The Wild Boar (2012)''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lee|first1=Esther Kim|title=The Theatre of David Henry Hwang|date=2015|publisher=Bloomsbury|isbn=978-1472512086|page=186}}</ref> In 2011 she worked with American composer [[Huang Ruo]] to write a [[libretto]] for an opera about ''[[Dr. Sun Yat-sen (opera)|Dr. Sun Yat-sen]]''. The completed work premiered at the [[National Centre for the Performing Arts (China)|National Centre for the Performing Arts]] in Beijing and later was adapted worldwide after it was well received.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Isaacs|first1=Gregory Sullivan|title=East Meets West|url=http://www.theaterjones.com/ntx/reviews/20140808181942/2014-08-15/Santa-Fe-Opera/Dr-Sun-Yat-sen|accessdate=16 November 2017|publisher=Theater Jones|date=15 August 2014}}</ref>
