[[File:CoralGablesCongregationalChurch.jpg|right|thumb|[[Coral Gables Congregational Church]]]] [[File:Rollins College Russell Theatre01.jpg|right|thumb|[[Annie Russell Theatre]]]] [[File:Miami Shores FL 361 NE 97th Street01.jpg|right|thumb|[[Building at 361 Northeast 97th Street]], [[Miami Shores, Florida|Miami Shores]]]] The architectural firm of '''Kiehnel and Elliot''' was established in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], in 1906. The firm did substantial work in [[Florida]], and moved to [[Miami]] in 1922.<ref name="histmiami">{{cite web |url=http://learningfrommiami.org/?p=1794 |title=Kiehnel & Elliott: A Brief Survey of the Firm’s Miami Projects |publisher=Learning from Miami |accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref> From 1926, it was known as '''Kiehnel, Elliot and Chalfant'''.<ref name="allegheny">{{cite web |url=http://alleghenywest.org/kiehnel-and-elliott/ |title=Kiehnel and Elliott |publisher=Allegheny West |accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref>
'''Richard Kiehnel''' (1870–1944) was the firm's senior partner. He was born in Germany and studied at the [[University of Breslau]] and the [[École nationale supérieure des Beaux-Arts]] in Paris. Kiehnel's first commission in the Miami area was in 1917 and he opened the firm's Miami office in 1922.<ref name="Kiehnel 1938">Kiehnel 1938</ref> He supervised the construction of El Jardin, the earliest known Mediterranean Revival work remaining in Miami. Designing the mansion for John Bindley, President of the [[Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel|Pittsburgh Steel Company]], Kiehnel departed from the Mission style that had only recently made its appearance in Florida and provided an elaborate antiquity for the house by using aging techniques to get the desired effect.<ref>Rodriguez 1982. p. 89</ref><ref>Patricios 1994. p. 177</ref> Kiehnel introduced Mediterranean Revival to Pinellas County through his designs of the [[Rolyat Hotel]] in [[Gulfport, Florida]] (now part of [[Stetson College of Law]]) and the [[Snell Arcade]] in [[St. Petersburg, Florida]].
Kiehnel advanced to Art Moderne styling in the Carlyle Hotel on Miami Beach and the 1924 Scottish Rite Masonic Temple on the Miami River, the first Art Deco building in the area.<ref name="Patricios 1994. p. 176">Patricios 1994. p. 176</ref> He also designed the [[Annie Russell Theatre]], a Romanesque Revival building on the campus of Rollins College in Winter Park.
Kiehnel was active in his profession. He was a member of the Pittsburgh chapter of the American Institute of Architects since 1906 and a member of the national body from 1913. He was a charter member of the Florida South chapter and its president in 1930-1931<ref>Kiehnel 1938.</ref> From 1935 to 1942 Kiehnel was the editor of Florida Architecture and Allied Arts magazine.
A number of Kiehnel's and the firm's works are listed on the U.S. [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref><ref name=miamishores>{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=64000116}} |author=Maria Tempkin|date=September 1988|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Miami Shores Thematic Group}}</ref>
